# Deployment — {{project_name}}

This is a fullstack monorepo: Express server (with Socket.io) and a Vite React web app. The Docker image bundles both — the server serves the built web assets — so a single Railway service is enough.

## Local development

Run server and web concurrently:

```bash
pnpm dev
```

- Web dev server: http://localhost:5173 (proxies `/api` and `/socket.io` to the server)
- API dev server: http://localhost:3000

## Local production

```bash
pnpm run build
pnpm --filter @{{project_slug}}/server start
```

## Docker

```bash
pnpm run docker:build
docker run --rm -p 3000:3000 {{docker_namespace}}/{{project_slug}}:latest
```

Tags produced:

```text
{{docker_namespace}}/{{project_slug}}:<package version>
{{docker_namespace}}/{{project_slug}}:latest
```

`docker-compose.yml` is provided for local stacks (and includes a commented Postgres service for when the project moves beyond JSON files).

## Railway

Railway deploys from the GitHub repo using `railway.toml`. One-time setup:

1. Push the project to GitHub.
2. In Railway, create a new project from the repository.
3. Set environment variables: `NODE_ENV=production`, `PORT` (Railway sets this automatically), `LOG_LEVEL`, `CORS_ORIGIN` (your public URL).
4. Railway picks up `railway.toml` and builds with the Dockerfile.
5. Subsequent pushes to the configured branch trigger redeploys.

The Dockerfile exposes port 3000 and the start command is `node dist/server.js`. Healthcheck is `/health`.

## Verification

```bash
pnpm run verify
```

For Docker / Railway changes also run:

```bash
pnpm run docker:build
docker run --rm -p 3000:3000 {{docker_namespace}}/{{project_slug}}:latest
# in another terminal:
curl http://localhost:3000/health
```
